        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-14T00:48:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh, wait wait wait, wait a sec (or…wait a tick!)\n\nWe’re starting with ticks_after_boot, which is a kernel USER_HZ clock_t, ticks. That’s better resolution than 1-second time_t, typically 100/second. Yet we’re throwing away the extra resolution and forcing everything to show up with a 1-second-truncated start time. We can do better! Let’s convert ticks_after_boot to a timeval instead of a time_t, and then add that to our computed boot_time.",
      "revId": "cf2ecb52e5f0f63e7a9903107f5195f8cc74db99",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
